tool.name: VegFrax_Fractional_Cover

param.name: in_low_res_path
param.dialogReference: A NetCDF of lower resolution satellite imagery captured from the COG Fetch module. Requires x, y and time dimensions with at least one variable.

param.name: in_high_res_path
param.dialogReference:
A GeoTIFF of high resolution classified imagery (e.g., vegetation type classes). Can be classified WorldView imagery or rasterised vegetation mapping polygons at a high resolution (e.g., 1 - 5 metres).

Note: input GeoTIFF must have only one band.

param.name: out_vegfrax_nc_path
param.dialogReference: The folder location and filename of the output NetCDF file containing VegFrax fractional classes NetCDF.

param.name: in_from_date
param.displayname: Subset date of low resolution data from
param.dialogReference:
The start date of the low resolution satellite data analysis period. All satellite data prior to this date will be excluded.

Note: this is helpful to restrict imagery down to a similar date matching the high resolution input.

param.name: in_to_date
param.displayname: Subset date of low resolution data to
param.dialogReference:
The end date of the low resolution satellite data analysis period. All satellite data after this date will be excluded.

Note: this is helpful to restrict imagery down to a similar date matching the high resolution input.

param.name: in_aggregator
param.dialogReference: The method used to aggregate pixel values within the lower resolution input NetCDF between the above requested dates. Options include median and mean.

param.name: in_classes
param.dialogReference:
The class or classes from the high resolution GeoTIFF that will be considered in fractional cover analysis. Each class is modelled separately, and all classes excluded from this list will be set to 0 (i.e., no class).

Note: as a general rule of thumb, select only the classes that are relevant to your target species or vegetation.

param.name: in_merge_classes
param.dialogReference: Whether or not to merge all selected classes into a single "presence" class. Useful if you have several classes that are all very similar and better treated as a single class.

param.name: in_num_samples
param.displayname: Number of random samples per class
param.dialogReference: The number of random samples generated per class that are used to train the Random Forest machine learning algorithm.

param.name: in_num_estimators
param.dialogReference: The number of estimators (or trees) in the Random Forest or Extra Trees algorithms.

param.name: in_num_validations
param.dialogReference: The number of model cross validations validations to perform. The more cross validations performed the longer processing takes, but the more accurate the model accuracy measures will be.

param.name: in_fmask_flags
param.expression: NoData | Valid | Cloud | Shadow | Snow | Water
param.dialogReference:
Classes captured within the OA measurement band provided for each satellite image via the DEA Fmask algorithm.

Only the selected pixel classes will be returned, whilst all others will be set to NoData (i.e., masked out).

param.name: in_max_cloud
param.dialogReference:
The maximum percentage of cloud cover existing per satellite image before it is discarded from analysis.

A value of 0 will return all satellite data with no cloud cover. A value of 10 will discard all satellite data with 11% or more cloud presence. A value of 100 will return all images regardless.

param.name: in_add_result_to_map
param.dialogReference: Whether to visualise the results to the currently active map once modelling is complete or not.

tool.summary:
VegFrax extracts pixel values in a high resolution classified image that fall within randomly selected low- to moderate-resolution pixels from another raster (e.g. Landsat or Sentinel) and determines the proportion of each of the different pixel classes within. Simply speaking, if a high-resolution raster has a pixel size of 1m and the moderate image has a pixel size of 10m, each random sample will have a window that captures 100 1m class pixels within - the percentage of each class in that window is calculated. For example, 25 forest pixels would = 25% forest.

The benefit of this method is two-fold: 1) fractional maps can be generated for lower-resolution images using high-resolution classification imagery; and 2) classified areas can be extrapolated outside of the classified image's extent via a random forest regressor and the band information inherent in the low- to moderate-resolution imagery. Insight into model fit is provided as the coefficient of determination (r-squared) for each class regression.
